[Student "E"]
{[showcards W:DA N:D3]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \CA. Seeing your \C3 he next played the \DA. What will you play on this trick?

Play the \D2.

Normally with this holding you would play the \D9 to encourage East to play a second \D through dummy's \D Q 10.

But this time you really want him to take his \CK. So play the discouraging \D2 and hope he gets the message to go back to \Cs. If he does play the \CK next it will win and he can then give you a \C ruff.}
[Play "W"]CA

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AKQ.AT.AJ4.QT862 985.KQ853.962.J4 642.964.KQ83.K73 JT73.J72.T75.A95"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "6a06c6b5bfd783b65bf988faddbed42c181b3518cfa79547f1a87c1964fda786"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards S:CQ]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \H5, you put on the \HJ, East won with the \HA. The second trick was \DA, \D2, \D3, \D5. The third trick was \DJ, \D6, \D8, \D7. East then put the \CQ on the table.

Play the \CA.

Does it look to you like East is trying to create an entry to dummy so he can cash the 2 \D winners? That's what he wants it to look like, hoping someone holds up their \CA.

But don't believe Declarer, believe your partner. On the first \D South played the \D2. On the second \D he played the \D6. He has an odd number of \Ds, obviously 3. And East must also have a third one, so he is up to some trickery with that \CQ.

So grab your \CA and return partner's \H suit. }
[Play "W"]H5

